1
00:00:06,268 --> 00:00:08,823
We have met the enemy 
and the enemy is us:

2
00:00:09,100 --> 00:00:12,768
[60s, 70s, 80s | Diminishing Expectations]

3
00:00:13,301 --> 00:00:15,453
arrogance,

4
00:00:17,323 --> 00:00:19,662
lack of humility,

5
00:00:20,432 --> 00:00:24,100
unwillingness to recognize 
your limitations,

6
00:00:25,690 --> 00:00:29,847
shortcomings, 
lack of qualification.

7
00:00:30,157 --> 00:00:34,643
Dainya, ātma-nivedana, 
goptṛtve varaṇa.

8
00:00:35,503 --> 00:00:39,012
So sometimes Bhakti Vinod 
lists first dainya.

9
00:00:39,612 --> 00:00:42,916
That you have to honestly admit 
 

10
00:00:43,070 --> 00:00:48,534
the hopelessness and helplessness 
of your situation

11
00:00:48,766 --> 00:00:50,892
of life, 
of human life.

12
00:00:51,152 --> 00:00:55,983
Not only can you not help others, 
you cannot help yourself.

13
00:00:56,653 --> 00:01:01,392
As Joni Mitchell once said 
on the 60s retrospective,

14
00:01:01,532 --> 00:01:04,047
she said, “By the end 
of the 60s

15
00:01:04,047 --> 00:01:06,177
we realised we couldn’t 
save the world.”

16
00:01:06,177 --> 00:01:08,792
She is talking about idealists.

17
00:01:09,072 --> 00:01:11,587
She said, “By the end 
of the 70s

18
00:01:11,587 --> 00:01:14,834
we realised we couldn’t 
save ourselves.

19
00:01:15,164 --> 00:01:19,171
So in the 80s”, she said 
sarcastically, facetiously,

20
00:01:19,171 --> 00:01:22,912
“we just decided 
to make money.”

21
00:01:23,832 --> 00:01:26,980
Oscar Wilde said, 
“When I was younger,

22
00:01:27,130 --> 00:01:30,308
I used to think 
money was everything.

23
00:01:30,718 --> 00:01:34,868
Now that I am older, 
I know it’s everything.”

24
00:01:35,348 --> 00:01:39,089
So, this type of cynicism.

25
00:01:39,529 --> 00:01:44,340
There is a fine line between 
a healthy scepticism

26
00:01:44,340 --> 00:01:48,411
about materialism 
and just being out and out cynical.

27
00:01:48,811 --> 00:01:52,780
Dainya … Bhakti Vinod is telling 
not becoming cynical,

28
00:01:52,880 --> 00:01:54,825
mean, nasty …

29
00:01:56,175 --> 00:01:59,582
always finding fault 
with everyone and everything.

30
00:01:59,582 --> 00:02:01,971
That’s not what 
he is talking about.

31
00:02:02,106 --> 00:02:04,879
He is talking 
about self-analysis.

32
00:02:05,210 --> 00:02:06,189
As Gurudev said,

33
00:02:06,199 --> 00:02:09,329
“My religion is finding 
fault with myself”,

34
00:02:09,419 --> 00:02:13,796
looking in yourself, 
and it’s not a cop-out

35
00:02:13,796 --> 00:02:16,063
or the …

36
00:02:16,673 --> 00:02:22,102
a sign of a weak mind, 
a weak-willed individual.

37
00:02:22,552 --> 00:02:25,240
To do an honest 
assessment of yourself

38
00:02:25,540 --> 00:02:31,892
and say, “Yes, I am, in a sense,
hopeless, helpless.”

39
00:02:32,982 --> 00:02:38,540
Humanism tries to awaken 
a competitive ego assertion,

40
00:02:38,940 --> 00:02:42,719
where you can 
envision yourself

41
00:02:42,929 --> 00:02:48,248
as an absolute center and try 
to extend the circumference

42
00:02:48,548 --> 00:02:51,858
or the range of your 
exploitative capacity

43
00:02:51,858 --> 00:02:54,843
like Ozymandias 
or Iron Man.

44
00:02:54,843 --> 00:02:58,271
Selfishness—you don’t owe 
anything anyone,

45
00:02:58,271 --> 00:03:01,959
you know, you’re number one, 
you’re the man, the whole thing …

46
00:03:02,204 --> 00:03:05,777
And why? 
Because I am worth it …

47
00:03:05,777 --> 00:03:09,049
That, all of that—
humanistic sloganeering.

48
00:03:10,049 --> 00:03:12,181
Whereas Guru Mahārāj 
would say,

49
00:03:12,181 --> 00:03:18,150
“Without the grace of Śrī Guru 
we are lifeless clay.”

50
00:03:21,200 --> 00:03:25,139
jogyatā-vichāre, kichu nāhi pāi

51
00:03:25,139 --> 00:03:28,527
Jogyatā means ‘qualification’.

52
00:03:28,527 --> 00:03:31,423
Jogyatā-vichāre—if you consider,

53
00:03:31,423 --> 00:03:35,165
if you analyse, 
what are my qualifications

54
00:03:35,165 --> 00:03:40,637
kichu nāhi pāi—
nothing, not even a little bit.

55
00:03:40,637 --> 00:03:45,434
See? That person would say, 
“Oh, don’t beat yourself up …

56
00:03:45,434 --> 00:03:49,236
You’ve got to believe in you, 
learning to love yourself

57
00:03:49,236 --> 00:03:54,717
is the greatest love of all ...”
Poor Whitney.

58
00:03:57,707 --> 00:04:05,246
Another humanistic empty, 
vapid humanistic slogan.

59
00:04:05,248 --> 00:04:10,601
No … The person who realizes 
their … does an honest assessment.

60
00:04:10,601 --> 00:04:15,149
Just like an athlete would 
of where your weak points are,

61
00:04:15,149 --> 00:04:18,350
where you need improvement, 
they get better.

62
00:04:18,350 --> 00:04:21,406
What does the athlete, 
who wants to improve, do?

63
00:04:21,406 --> 00:04:24,146
Play with people 
who are better than them.

64
00:04:24,146 --> 00:04:26,683
Not with whom they can defeat,

65
00:04:26,683 --> 00:04:29,089
they want to play with someone 
they can’t defeat.

66
00:04:29,089 --> 00:04:30,638
That makes you better.

67
00:04:30,638 --> 00:04:35,987
Ajita means ‘undefeatable’, 
‘unconquerable’.

68
00:04:35,987 --> 00:04:42,255
So the person who makes 
a realistic assessment of themselves,

69
00:04:42,255 --> 00:04:50,030
say, like iron, they can be interested 
in the philosopher’s stone,

70
00:04:50,030 --> 00:04:52,370
the cintamani, the sparsamani

71
00:04:52,370 --> 00:04:55,733
that converts iron into gold.

72
00:04:55,733 --> 00:05:01,166
Silver may not feel 
the necessity for gold so much.

73
00:05:01,166 --> 00:05:07,078
—“I’m silver, I’m ok, 
happy being silver.”

74
00:05:07,078 --> 00:05:15,735
But who has a more real … 
not an unrealistic,

75
00:05:15,735 --> 00:05:19,583
they have low self‒esteem, 
they are just beating themselves up,

76
00:05:19,583 --> 00:05:21,459
that is not what 
we are talking about.

77
00:05:21,459 --> 00:05:23,844
A realistic assessment.

